<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-080-064  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 080 064.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Feb 20 1989 v15 n4 p110(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Going gets tougher in communications. (equipment forecasts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Franchi, Madeline.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>New orders for communications equipment peaked in the firstquarter of 1988, reaching $7.67 in October 1988, but a continueddecline is expected.andP;  Orders for military equipment are showingthe most reduction, but growth of new orders in the commercialsector are not expected to increase more than one percent.andO;Shipments of communications equipment fell by 0.7 percent fromOctober 1988 to November 1988, but 1989 shipments of defenseequipment will increase by two percent while shipments ofcommercial equipment will drop by one percent.andP;  A one to twopercent increase in business purchases of equipment is expected,after hitting an annualized $36.4 billion in the third quarter of1988.andP;  The cutback in defense orders is also causing low backlogs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Communications EquipmentForecastingSalesMarket Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Communication equipment shipments 1986-1990. (graph)Defense versus commercial shipments 1984-1990. (graph)Communication equipment backlogs 1984-1990. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>